You are extracting UBX-NAV-RELPOSNED from u-blox PDF manual pages.

This message has TWO different structures:

**UBX-NAV-RELPOSNED-V0 (40 bytes, M8/older):**
| Offset | Type | Name |
|--------|------|------|
| 0 | U1 | version (0x00) |
| 1 | U1 | reserved1 |
| 2 | U2 | refStationId |
| 4 | U4 | iTOW |
| 8 | I4 | relPosN |
| 12 | I4 | relPosE |
| 16 | I4 | relPosD |
| 20 | I1 | relPosHPN |
| 21 | I1 | relPosHPE |
| 22 | I1 | relPosHPD |
| 23 | U1 | reserved2 |
| 24 | U4 | accN |
| 28 | U4 | accE |
| 32 | U4 | accD |
| 36 | X4 | flags |

**UBX-NAV-RELPOSNED-V1 (64 bytes, F9/newer):**
| Offset | Type | Name |
|--------|------|------|
| 0 | U1 | version (0x01) |
| 1 | U1 | reserved0 |
| 2 | U2 | refStationId |
| 4 | U4 | iTOW |
| 8 | I4 | relPosN |
| 12 | I4 | relPosE |
| 16 | I4 | relPosD |
| 20 | I4 | relPosLength |
| 24 | I4 | relPosHeading |
| 28 | U4 | reserved1 |
| 32 | I1 | relPosHPN |
| 33 | I1 | relPosHPE |
| 34 | I1 | relPosHPD |
| 35 | I1 | relPosHPLength |
| 36 | U4 | accN |
| 40 | U4 | accE |
| 44 | U4 | accD |
| 48 | U4 | accLength |
| 52 | U4 | accHeading |
| 56 | U4 | reserved2 |
| 60 | X4 | flags |

Check payload length: 40 bytes = V0, 64 bytes = V1.

IMPORTANT: Name the message based on which version the PDF documents:
- If payload is 40 bytes: name = "UBX-NAV-RELPOSNED-V0"
- If payload is 64 bytes: name = "UBX-NAV-RELPOSNED-V1"

Return using ubx_message_extraction tool.

extracted_structure.name: UBX-NAV-RELPOSNED-V0
extracted_structure.description: Relative positioning information in NED frame

fields.name: refStationId
fields.description: Reference Station ID. Must be in the range 0..4095

fields.name: iTOW
fields.description: GPS time of week of the navigation epoch. See the description of iTOW for details.

fields.name: relPosN
fields.description: North component of relative position vector

fields.name: relPosE
fields.description: East component of relative position vector

fields.name: relPosD
fields.description: Down component of relative position vector

fields.name: relPosHPN
fields.description: High-precision North component of relative position vector. Must be in the range -99 to +99. The full North component of the relative position vector, in units of cm, is given by relPosN + (relPosHPN * 1e-2)

fields.name: relPosHPE
fields.description: High-precision East component of relative position vector. Must be in the range -99 to +99. The full East component of the relative position vector, in units of cm, is given by relPosE + (relPosHPE * 1e-2)

fields.name: relPosHPD
fields.description: High-precision Down component of relative position vector. Must be in the range -99 to +99. The full Down component of the relative position vector, in units of cm, is given by relPosD + (relPosHPD * 1e-2)

fields.name: accN
fields.description: Accuracy of relative position North component

fields.name: accE
fields.description: Accuracy of relative position East component

fields.name: accD
fields.description: Accuracy of relative position Down component

bitfield_members.name: gnssFixOK
bitfield_members.description: A valid fix (i.e within DOP & accuracy masks)

bitfield_members.name: relPosValid
bitfield_members.description: 1 if relative position components and accuracies are valid

bitfield_members.name: carrSoln
bitfield_members.description: Carrier phase range solution status: 0 = no carrier phase range solution, 1 = carrier phase range solution with floating ambiguities, 2 = carrier phase range solution with fixed ambiguities

bitfield_members.name: isMoving
bitfield_members.description: 1 if the receiver is operating in moving baseline mode (not supported in protocol versions less than 20.3)

bitfield_members.name: refPosMiss
bitfield_members.description: 1 if extrapolated reference position was used to compute moving baseline solution this epoch (not supported in protocol versions less than 20.3)

bitfield_members.name: refObsMiss
bitfield_members.description: 1 if extrapolated reference observations were used to compute moving baseline solution this epoch (not supported in protocol versions less than 20.3)
